The describe function shows the following information about each column in the dataset:

  • The number of non-null values
  • Mean
  • Standard deviation
  • Minimum value
  • 25th percentile
  • 50th percentile (median)
  • 75th percentile
  • Maximum value

This function shows the mentioned values for numeric columns only. To show the values for all columns, we can use the include='all' parameter.

This function has a percentiles parameter that can be used to specify the percentiles to be shown. The default value is [.25, .5, .75], which are the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles.

# using a copy to be able to run the cell multiple times
cleaned = df.copy()
cleaned['Age'].fillna(df['Age'].mean(), inplace=True)
# drop cabin column as it has too many missing values
cleaned.drop('Cabin', axis=1, inplace=True)
# as the embarked column has only 2 missing values, we can drop the rows
cleaned.dropna(subset=['Embarked'], inplace=True)
cleaned.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

Advantages of using mean for filling the missing values:

  • the mean of the data does not change
  • it is easy
  • if the approximate value is mean, then it is a good approximation

Disadvantages of using mean for filling the missing values:

  • it is useful only for numeric data
  • it may destroy the relationship between the data and the target variable
  • standard derivation is not considered
  • the distribution of the data may change

Part 8¶

In [ ]:
def loopQueenstownPriceAvg():
    sum = 0
    count = 0
    for index, row in cleaned.iterrows():
        if row['Embarked'] == embarked['Q']:
            sum += row['Fare']
            count += 1
    return sum / count
print("Average price of tickets for passengers embarked in Queenstown: ", loopQueenstownPriceAvg())

Average price of tickets for passengers embarked in Queenstown:  13.276029870129872
In [ ]:
from timeit import timeit

num = 100
vectorization = timeit(vectorizationQueenstownPriceAvg, number=num)
loop = timeit(loopQueenstownPriceAvg, number=num)
print("Vectorization:", vectorization)
print("Loop:", loop)
print("Vectorization is", loop / vectorization, "times faster")

Vectorization: 0.06120409999994081
Loop: 3.388810199999625
Vectorization is 55.36900632478711 times faster

As the results indicate, the vectorized function is about 55 times faster than the for loop.

def plotNormal(idx, mean, std, label, color):
    y = sp.stats.norm.pdf(x, mean, std)
    axes[idx].plot(x, y, label=label, color=color)
    axes[idx].legend()

def plot(idx, name, row):
    plotNormal(idx, row['Survived Mean'], row['Survived Std'], 'Survived', 'blue')
    plotNormal(idx, row['Not Survived Mean'], row['Not Survived Std'], 'Not Survived', 'red')
    axes[idx].set_title(name)

for idx, (name, row) in enumerate(info.iterrows()):
    plot(idx, name, row)

In order to predict whether a passenger will survive or not, we'd better use a feature that is highly correlated with the Survived column. The Sex column is highly correlated with the Survived column, so we can use it to predict whether a passenger will survive or not.

In [ ]:
def getCollisionPoints(mean1, std1, mean2, std2):
    a = 1 / (2 * std1**2) - 1 / (2 * std2**2)
    b = mean2 / (std2**2) - mean1 / (std1**2)
    c = mean1**2 / (2 * std1**2) - mean2**2 / (2 * std2**2) - np.log(std2 / std1)
    res = np.roots([a, b, c])
    res.sort()
    return res
In [ ]:
def willSurvive(normalizedX, collisionPoints, survivedInMiddle):
    if survivedInMiddle:
        return 1 if collisionPoints[0] < normalizedX < collisionPoints[1] else 0
    else:
        return 1 if normalizedX < collisionPoints[0] or normalizedX > collisionPoints[1] else 0

In the following block, the survivedInMiddle dictionary indicates whether the majority of the passengers survived in the middle of the plot or not.

In [ ]:
survivedInMiddle = {
    'Pclass': 0,
    'Sex': 0,
    'Age': 0,
    'SibSp': 1,
    'Parch': 1,
    'Fare': 0,
    'Embarked': 0
}

df = pd.DataFrame()
collisionPoints = {}
for idx, (name, row) in enumerate(info.iterrows()):
    collisionPoints[str(name)] = getCollisionPoints(row['Survived Mean'], row['Survived Std'], row['Not Survived Mean'], row['Not Survived Std'])
    df[name] = normalizedDf[str(name)].apply(lambda x: willSurvive(x, collisionPoints[str(name)], survivedInMiddle[str(name)]))
    correct = df.loc[df[str(name)] == cleaned['Survived']].shape[0]
    print(f"{name:8} -> Correct Predictions: {correct} | Accuracy: {correct / df.shape[0] * 100:.2f}%")
